Most of the chemical diversity of wood (colour, fragrance and durability) is embedded in the extractives 
i.e.
the non-structural components that are solubilized by solvents with different polarities, and that include a diverse array of chemical families. In the case of the lipophilic soluble fraction extracted by non-polar solvents such as dichloromethane, hexane or petroleum ether, the chemical families include mainly fatty acids and alcohols, phytosterols, hydrocarbons and triterpenes (
Fengel and Wegener, 1984
; 
Hillis, 1962
; 
Hon and Shiraishi, 2001
).

Some of these compounds have received attention due to their potential interest as bioactive and functional molecules and to the possibility of integrating extractives recovery as a process step in biorefineries (
Christopher, 2012
). Moreover, some wood lipophilic extractives may be a nuisance in pulp processing, because of equipment fouling and product staining (
Hillis, 1962
; Sjostr ¨¨om and 
Marchessault, 1993
; 
Valto et al., 2012
).

