Fatty acids were the major family, representing 40.8% of the total compounds (as % of total area), followed by phytosterols (19.0%), aromatics (10.5%) and triterpenes (10.4%) (
Fig. 3
).

Phytosterols content was 
186.1 mg
/g of extract (
Table 2
), where β- sitosterol (peak 
118
) and stigmastanol (peak 
119
) represented 80% and 7% of the total sterols, and with the presence of minor amounts of fucosterol (peak 
121
), and stigmast-4-en-3-one (peak 
128
).

The aromatic compounds accounted for 
87.3 mg
/g of extract (
Table 3
), where syringic acid (peak 
25
), vanillic acid (peak 
14
), syringaldehyde (peak 
12
), and vanillin (peak 
5
) were the most abundant compounds with respectively 14.6, 12.2, 12.0 and 
8.2 mg
/g of extract.

In spite the fact that the lipophilic content (by DCM extraction) of 

E. globulus

wood was low in all the samples studied, since it ranged from only 0.2–0.5% of the oven dry wood mass (
Fig. 1
), the composition and the variability along the tree of the extractives are more important than only their content. This was the driver for this study, where a detailed and comprehensive composition of the DCM extracts from sapwood, outer heartwood and inner heartwood at different height levels (0%, 30% and 65%) were obtained. In fact, it was possible to identify 202 compounds in the DCM extracts, an extremely high number of compounds when compared to other works with eucalyptus that only reported up to 88 compounds (
Freire et al., 2006
, 
2002
; Guti´errez et al., 1999; 
Rencoret et al., 2007
). In addition to the targeted design of this study that aimed at considering all compounds regardless of their content, the age of the trees (40 years) is above that of the previously studied trees (8–12 years) and this may contribute to increase the number of extractives since it is known that age favours the accumulation of some secondary metabolites (
Hillis, 1962
).

